Definition A.7. For any inverse semigroup $T$, one can define the left-cancellative category $L(T)$ whose objects are the idempotents of $T$. A morphism $e\to f$ is an element $t\in T$ satisfying $e=t^{*}t$ and $t=ft$.
Definition 3.4. A category $\mathbf{A}$ is called a poset-group-amalgamation when there exist a partial order $P$ and a group $G$ such that: (A1) there is a weak initial object $0$, unique up to isomorphism; (A2) there is a faithful retraction $F$ of the inclusion $\mathbf{A}(0,0)\hookrightarrow\mathbf{A}$; (A3) there is an isomorphism $\alpha\colon\mathbf{A}(0,0)\to G^{\mathrm{op}}$ of monoids; (A4) there is an equivalence $\smash{\xymatrix@1{(\mathbf{A},\leq)\ar@<1ex>|-{\beta}[r]&P\ar@<.5ex>|-{\beta^% {\prime}}[l]}}$ of preorders; (A5) for each object $x$ there is an isomorphism $f\colon x\to\beta^{\prime}(\beta(x))$ with $\alpha F(f)=1$; (A6) for each $y$ and $m$ there is an isomorphism $f\colon x\to y$ with $\alpha F(f)=m$.
Definition A.3. For any inverse semigroup $T$, one can define the groupoid $G(T)$ whose objects are the idempotents of $T$, i.e. the elements $e\in T$ with $e^{2}=e$. A morphism $e\to f$ is an element $t\in T$ satisfying $e=t^{*}t$ and $tt^{*}=f$.
Definition 3.1. An action of a monoid $M$ on a category $\mathbf{C}$ is a functor $F\colon M\to\mathbf{Cat}(\mathbf{C},\mathbf{C})$. Write $mx$ for the action of $Fm$ on an object $x$ of $\mathbf{C}$, and $mf$ for the action of $Fm$ on a morphism $f$ of $\mathbf{C}$.
Definition 7.2. Define a presheaf $\mathrm{Aut}\in\mathrm{PSh}(\mathcal{C}_{\rightarrowtail})$ by $\displaystyle\mathrm{Aut}(C)$ $\displaystyle=\{i\colon C\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\cong}}{{\to}}C^{\prime}\mid C% ^{\prime}\in\mathcal{C}\},$ $\displaystyle\mathrm{Aut}\big{(}C\stackrel{{\scriptstyle k}}{{\rightarrowtail}% }D\big{)}\big{(}j\colon D\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\cong}}{{\to}}D^{\prime}\big{)}$ $\displaystyle=j\big{|}_{k(C)}\circ k\colon C\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\cong}}{{% \to}}j(k(C)).$
Definition 18. Given a filter of ideals $\mathbb{F}$ in a commutative ring $R$ and an $R$-module $D$, we say that $D$ is $\mathbb{F}$-divisible [26, Section VI.9] if $R/I\otimes_{R}D=0$ for all $I\in\mathbb{F}$.
Definition 19. Let $u\colon R\longrightarrow U$ be an epimorphism of commutative rings. We say that an $R$-module $D$ is $u$-divisible (or $u$-h-divisible) [7, Remark 1.2(1)] if $D$ is a quotient $R$-module of a $U$-module.
Definition 6.11. An sp-filtration $\varphi$ is said to satisfy the weak Cousin condition if whenever $\mathfrak{p}$ and $\mathfrak{q}$ are prime ideals such that $\mathfrak{p}\subsetneq\mathfrak{q}$ and $\mathfrak{p}$ is maximal under $\mathfrak{q}$ (i.e. there is no prime ideal $\mathfrak{t}$ such that $\mathfrak{p}\subsetneq\mathfrak{t}\subsetneq\mathfrak{q}$), then we have $\forall j\in\mathbb{Z},\ \mathfrak{q}\in\varphi(j)\Rightarrow\mathfrak{p}\in% \varphi(j-1)$
Definition 3.2. Let $R$ be a commutative noetherian ring. Given a complex $X$ in ${\sf{D}}(R)$, we define the following subsets of $\operatorname{\mathsf{Spec}}(R)$: • $\operatorname{\mathsf{supp}}(X):=\{\mathfrak{p}\in\operatorname{\mathsf{Spec}}% (R)\colon X\otimes_{R}^{\mathbb{L}}k(\mathfrak{p})\neq 0\}$, called the (small) support of $X$; • $\operatorname{\mathsf{Supp}}(X):=\{\mathfrak{p}\in\operatorname{\mathsf{Spec}}% (R)\colon X_{\mathfrak{p}}\neq 0\}$, called the big support of $X$. The (big) support of a subcategory $\mathcal{X}$ of ${\sf{D}}(R)$ is the union of the (big) supports of the objects in $\mathcal{X}$.
Definition 2.4. If $\mathcal{G}$ is locally coherent, a torsion pair $\mathbf{t}=(\mathcal{T},\mathcal{F})$ in $\mathcal{G}$ is said to be restrictable if $\mathbf{t}\cap\mathsf{fp}(\mathcal{G}):=(\mathcal{T}\cap\mathsf{fp}(\mathcal{G% }),\mathcal{F}\cap\mathsf{fp}(\mathcal{G}))$ is a torsion pair in $\mathsf{fp}(\mathcal{G})$.
Definition 2.9. A pair of subcategories $\mathbb{T}:=(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V})$ in a triangulated category $\mathcal{D}$ is a $t$-structure if (1) $\operatorname{\mathsf{Hom}}_{\mathcal{D}}(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V})=0$; (2) $\mathcal{U}[1]\subseteq\mathcal{U}$; (3) $\mathcal{U}\ast\mathcal{V}=\mathcal{D}$. In that case, we call $\mathcal{U}$ the aisle, $\mathcal{V}$ the coaisle and $\mathcal{H}_{\mathbb{T}}=\mathcal{V}[1]\cap\mathcal{U}$ the heart of $\mathbb{T}$. The $t$-structure $\mathbb{T}$ is said to be nondegenerate if $\cap_{n\in\mathbb{Z}}\mathcal{U}[n]=0=\cap_{n\in\mathbb{Z}}\mathcal{V}[n]$ and bounded if $\cup_{n\in\mathbb{Z}}\mathcal{U}[n]=\mathcal{D}=\cup_{n\in\mathbb{Z}}\mathcal{% V}[n]$.
Definition 2.3. A torsion pair in a Grothendieck abelian category is said to be of finite type if its torsionfree class is closed under direct limits.
Definition 4.9. A hereditary torsion pair $\mathbf{t}=(\mathcal{T},\mathcal{F})$ in a module category is said to be perfect if the associated Giraud subcategory $\mathcal{T}^{\perp_{0,1}}$ admits a right adjoint to the inclusion functor.
Definition 2.18. We say that an intermediate $t$-structure $\mathbb{T}$ in ${\sf{D}}(R)$ with heart $\mathcal{H}_{\mathbb{T}}$ induces a (bounded) derived equivalence if $\mathsf{real}_{\mathbb{T}}$ (respectively, $\mathsf{real}^{b}_{\mathbb{T}}$) is an equivalence. In that case we say that $\mathcal{H}_{\mathbb{T}}$ and $\mathsf{Mod}(R)$ are (bounded) derived equivalent.
Definition 2.1. A pair $(\mathcal{T},\mathcal{F})$ of subcategories of an abelian category $\mathcal{A}$ is said to be a torsion pair if (1) $\operatorname{\mathsf{Hom}}_{\mathcal{A}}(T,F)=0$ for any $T$ in $\mathcal{T}$ and any $F$ in $\mathcal{F}$. (2) For any $X$ in $\mathcal{A}$, there are objects $t(X)$ in $\mathcal{T}$ and $f(X)$ in $\mathcal{F}$, and a short exact sequence $0\longrightarrow t(X)\longrightarrow X\longrightarrow f(X)\longrightarrow 0.$ If $\mathbf{t}:=(\mathcal{T},\mathcal{F})$ is a torsion pair in $\mathcal{A}$, $\mathcal{T}$ is called its torsion class and $\mathcal{F}$ its torsionfree class. The pair $\mathbf{t}$ is said to be hereditary if $\mathcal{T}$ is closed under subobjects, and cohereditary if $\mathcal{F}$ is closed under quotient objects. A subcategory $\mathcal{V}$ of $\mathcal{A}$ is called a torsion torsionfree class (TTF class, for short) if there are torsion pairs $(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V})$ and $(\mathcal{V},\mathcal{W})$ in $\mathcal{A}$, i.e. if $\mathcal{V}$ is both a torsion class and a torsionfree class in $\mathcal{A}$.
Definition 3.5. Let $\mathcal{D}$ be a triangulated category admitting arbitrary (set-indexed) coproducts. A subcategory $\mathcal{L}$ of $\mathcal{D}$ is said to be localising if $\mathcal{L}$ is a triangulated subcategory closed under coproducts. A localising subcategory $\mathcal{L}$ is furthermore said to be smashing if $\mathcal{L}^{\perp}$ is closed under coproducts.
Definition 4.2. Let $R$ be a commutative noetherian ring and $\mathbb{T}$ a nondegenerate smashing $t$-structure in ${\sf{D}}(R)$, with heart $\mathcal{H}_{\mathbb{T}}$. A set $U\subseteq\operatorname{\mathsf{Spec}}(R)$ is called a $\mathcal{H}_{\mathbb{T}}$-support if it is the support of a hereditary torsion class in $\mathcal{H}_{\mathbb{T}}$. This torsion class will then be $\operatorname{\mathsf{supp}}^{-1}(U)\cap\mathcal{H}_{\mathbb{T}}$.
Definition 2.11. For a ring $R$, a $t$-structure $\mathbb{T}=(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V})$ in ${\sf{D}}(R)$ is said to be • intermediate if there are integers $a<b$ such that $\mathbb{D}^{\leq a}\subseteq\mathcal{U}\subseteq\mathbb{D}^{\leq b}$; • smashing if $\mathcal{V}$ is closed under coproducts; • homotopically smashing if $\mathcal{V}$ is closed under directed homotopy colimits; • compactly generated if there is a set of compact objects $\mathcal{S}$ in $\mathcal{U}$ such that $\mathcal{V}=\mathcal{S}^{\bot}$. • cosilting if $\mathbb{T}=({}^{\bot_{\leq 0}}C,{}^{\bot_{>0}}C)$ for some object $C$ of ${\sf{D}}(R)$ (then called a cosilting object); • cotilting if it is cosilting and $C^{I}$ lies in ${}^{\bot_{\neq 0}}C$ for all sets $I$ (in this case $C$ is said to be cotilting). If $R$ is coherent, we say that $\mathbb{T}$ is restrictable if the pair $(\mathcal{U}\cap{\sf{D}}^{b}(\mathsf{mod}(R)),\mathcal{V}\cap{\sf{D}}^{b}(% \mathsf{mod}(R)))$ is a $t$-structure of the triangulated subcategory ${\sf{D}}^{b}(\mathsf{mod}(R))$ of ${\sf{D}}(R)$.
Definition 5.1. We say that a torsion pair $\mathbf{t}=(\mathcal{T},\mathcal{F})$ in $\mathcal{A}$ induces a (bounded) derived equivalence if the associated HRS-tilt induces a (bounded) derived equivalence (in the sense of Definition 2.18).
Definition 3.1. A subset $\mathcal{P}$ of $\operatorname{\mathsf{Spec}}(R)$ is said to be specialisation-closed if for any $\mathfrak{p}$ in $\mathcal{P}$ we have that $\mbox{\larger\larger$\vee$}(\mathfrak{p})$ is contained in $\mathcal{P}$. Dually, the subset $\mathcal{P}$ is called generalisation-closed if for any $\mathfrak{p}$ in $\mathcal{P}$ we have that $\mbox{\larger\larger$\wedge$}(\mathfrak{p})$ is contained in $\mathcal{P}$.
Definition 6.13. Let $R$ be a commutative noetherian ring. We say that an sp-filtration $\varphi$ in $\operatorname{\mathsf{Spec}}(R)$ is restrictable if the associated compactly generated $t$-structure is restrictable (in other words, the associated $t$-structure is in the image of the assignment $\Theta$).
Definition 3.9. Let $R$ be a commutative noetherian ring. A function $\varphi$ from $\mathbb{Z}$ to the power set of $\operatorname{\mathsf{Spec}}(R)$ is said to be an sp-filtration of $\operatorname{\mathsf{Spec}}(R)$ if $\varphi$ is a decreasing function between posets (i.e. if for all integers $n$, $\varphi(n)\supseteq\varphi(n+1)$) and $\varphi(n)$ is specialisation-closed, for all $n$.
Definition 2.38. We say that an $\infty$-category ${\mathcal{M}}$ weakly left tensored over a monoidal $\infty$-category ${\mathcal{V}}$ is pseudo-enriched in ${\mathcal{V}}$ if condition 1. of Lemma 2.37 holds for any ${\mathrm{X}},{\mathrm{Y}}\in{\mathcal{M}}.$ We say that an $\infty$-category ${\mathcal{M}}$ weakly left tensored over a monoidal $\infty$-category ${\mathcal{V}}$ is enriched in ${\mathcal{V}}$ (in the sense of Lurie) if condition 1. and 2. of Lemma 2.37 holds for any ${\mathrm{X}},{\mathrm{Y}}\in{\mathcal{M}}.$
Definition 2.12. We call a ${\mathcal{O}}$-monoidal $\infty$-category ${\mathcal{C}}\to{\mathcal{O}}$ compatible with small colimits if for any ${\mathrm{X}}\in{\mathcal{O}}_{[1]}$ the fiber ${\mathcal{C}}_{\mathrm{X}}$ has small colimits and for any active morphism ${\mathrm{X}}\to{\mathrm{Y}}$ in ${\mathcal{O}}$ with ${\mathrm{Y}}\in{\mathcal{O}}_{[1]}$ the induced functor $\prod_{{\mathrm{i}}=1}^{\mathrm{n}}{\mathcal{C}}_{{\mathrm{X}}_{\mathrm{i}}}% \simeq{\mathcal{C}}_{\mathrm{X}}\to{\mathcal{C}}_{\mathrm{Y}}$ preserves small colimits component-wise. We say that a ${\mathcal{O}}$-monoidal functor ${\mathcal{C}}\to{\mathcal{D}}$ preserves small colimits if for any ${\mathrm{X}}\in{\mathcal{O}}_{[1]}$ the induced functor ${\mathcal{C}}_{\mathrm{X}}\to{\mathcal{D}}_{\mathrm{X}}$ preserves small colimits.
Definition 3.5. Given a space ${\mathrm{X}}$ and a small $\infty$-operad ${\mathcal{V}}$ an $\infty$-precategory weakly enriched in ${\mathcal{V}}$ with space of objects ${\mathrm{X}}$ is an $\infty$-precategory enriched in ${\mathcal{V}}^{\prime}$ with space of objects ${\mathrm{X}}$.
Definition 2.24. Let ${\mathcal{V}}\to{\mathrm{Ass}},{\mathcal{W}}\to{\mathrm{Ass}}$ be generalized $\infty$-operads and $\phi=(\phi_{1},\phi_{2}):{\mathcal{M}}\to{\mathcal{V}}\times{\mathcal{W}}$ a map of cocartesian fibrations relative to the inert morphisms of ${\mathrm{Ass}}\times{\mathrm{Ass}}$, whose first component preserves the maximum and whose second component preserves the minimum. We call $\phi:{\mathcal{M}}\to{\mathcal{V}}\times{\mathcal{W}}$ an $\infty$-category weakly bitensored over $({\mathcal{V}},{\mathcal{W}})$ (or an $\infty$-category with weak biaction over $({\mathcal{V}},{\mathcal{W}})$) if the following conditions hold: (1) for every ${\mathrm{n}},{\mathrm{m}}\geq 0$ the map $[0]\simeq\{{\mathrm{n}}\}\subset[{\mathrm{n}}]$ in the first component and the map $[0]\simeq\{0\}\subset[{\mathrm{m}}]$ in the second component induce an equivalence $\theta:{\mathcal{M}}_{[{\mathrm{n}}][{\mathrm{m}}]}\to{\mathcal{V}}_{[{\mathrm% {n}}]}\times_{{\mathcal{V}}_{[0]}}{\mathcal{M}}_{[0][0]}\times_{{\mathcal{W}}_% {[0]}}{\mathcal{W}}_{[{\mathrm{m}}]},$ (2) for every ${\mathrm{X}},{\mathrm{Y}}\in{\mathcal{M}}$ lying over $([{\mathrm{m}}],[{\mathrm{m}}^{\prime}]),([{\mathrm{n}}],[{\mathrm{n}}^{\prime% }])\in{\mathrm{Ass}}\times{\mathrm{Ass}}$ the cocartesian lift ${\mathrm{Y}}\to{\mathrm{Y}}^{\prime}$ of the map $[0]\simeq\{{\mathrm{n}}\}\subset[{\mathrm{n}}]$ and $[0]\simeq\{0\}\subset[{\mathrm{n}}^{\prime}]$ induces a pullback square $\xy\xymatrix{{\mathcal{M}}({\mathrm{X}},{\mathrm{Y}})\ar[d]\ar[r]&{\mathcal{V}% }(\phi_{1}({\mathrm{X}}),\phi_{1}({\mathrm{Y}}))\times{\mathcal{W}}(\phi_{2}({% \mathrm{X}}),\phi_{2}({\mathrm{Y}}))\times{\mathcal{M}}({\mathrm{X}},{\mathrm{% Y}}^{\prime})\ar[d]\\ {\mathrm{Ass}}([{\mathrm{m}}],[{\mathrm{n}}])\times{\mathrm{Ass}}([{\mathrm{m}% }^{\prime}],[{\mathrm{n}}^{\prime}])\ar[r]&{\mathrm{Ass}}([{\mathrm{m}}],[{% \mathrm{n}}])\times{\mathrm{Ass}}([{\mathrm{m}}^{\prime}],[{\mathrm{n}}^{% \prime}])\times{\mathrm{Ass}}([{\mathrm{m}}],[0])\times{\mathrm{Ass}}([{% \mathrm{m}}^{\prime}],[0]).}$ We call $\phi:{\mathcal{M}}\to{\mathcal{V}}$ an $\infty$-category bitensored over $({\mathcal{V}},{\mathcal{W}})$ (or an $\infty$-category with $({\mathcal{V}},{\mathcal{W}})$-biaction) if ${\mathcal{V}},{\mathcal{W}}$ are monoidal $\infty$-categories, $\phi$ is a map of cocartesian fibrations over ${\mathrm{Ass}}\times{\mathrm{Ass}}$ and condition 1. holds (condition 2. is then automatic).
Definition 7.1. Let ${\mathcal{C}}$ be an $\infty$-precategory (weakly) enriched in an $\infty$-operad ${\mathcal{V}}$ with small space of objects ${\mathrm{X}}.$ We call ${\mathcal{C}}$ an $\infty$-category (weakly) enriched in ${\mathcal{V}}$ if $\iota:{\mathrm{X}}\to{\mathrm{L}}({\mathcal{C}})^{\simeq}$ is an equivalence.
Definition 2.18. Let ${\mathcal{V}}\to{\mathrm{Ass}}$ be a generalized $\infty$-operad and $\phi:{\mathcal{M}}\to{\mathcal{V}}$ a map of cocartesian fibrations relative to the inert morphisms of ${\mathrm{Ass}}$ that preserve the maximum. We call $\phi:{\mathcal{M}}\to{\mathcal{V}}$ an $\infty$-category weakly left tensored over ${\mathcal{V}}$ (or an $\infty$-category with weak left ${\mathcal{V}}$-action) if the following conditions hold: (1) for every ${\mathrm{n}}\geq 0$ the map $[0]\simeq\{{\mathrm{n}}\}\subset[{\mathrm{n}}]$ in $\Delta$ induces an equivalence $\theta:{\mathcal{M}}_{[{\mathrm{n}}]}\to{\mathcal{V}}_{[{\mathrm{n}}]}\times_{% {\mathcal{V}}_{[0]}}{\mathcal{M}}_{[0]}.$ (2) for every ${\mathrm{X}},{\mathrm{Y}}\in{\mathcal{M}}$ lying over $[{\mathrm{m}}],[{\mathrm{n}}]\in{\mathrm{Ass}}$ the cocartesian lift ${\mathrm{Y}}\to{\mathrm{Y}}^{\prime}$ of the map $[0]\simeq\{{\mathrm{n}}\}\subset[{\mathrm{n}}]$ in $\Delta$ induces a pullback square $\xy\xymatrix{{\mathcal{M}}({\mathrm{X}},{\mathrm{Y}})\ar[d]\ar[r]&{\mathcal{V}% }(\phi({\mathrm{X}}),\phi({\mathrm{Y}}))\times{\mathcal{M}}({\mathrm{X}},{% \mathrm{Y}}^{\prime})\ar[d]\\ {\mathrm{Ass}}([{\mathrm{m}}],[{\mathrm{n}}])\ar[r]&{\mathrm{Ass}}([{\mathrm{m% }}],[{\mathrm{n}}])\times{\mathrm{Ass}}([{\mathrm{m}}],[0]).}$ We call $\phi:{\mathcal{M}}\to{\mathcal{V}}$ an $\infty$-category left tensored over ${\mathcal{V}}$ if ${\mathcal{V}}$ is a monoidal $\infty$-category, $\phi$ is a map of cocartesian fibrations over ${\mathrm{Ass}}$ and condition 1. holds (condition 2. is then automatic).
Definition 3.2. Gepner-Haugseng Given a space ${\mathrm{X}}$ and an $\infty$-operad ${\mathcal{V}}$ an $\infty$-precategory enriched in ${\mathcal{V}}$ (or ${\mathcal{V}}$-precategory) with space of objects ${\mathrm{X}}$ is a map ${\mathrm{Ass}}_{{\mathrm{X}}}\to{\mathcal{V}}$ of generalized $\infty$-operads.
Definition 2.10. Let $\psi:{\mathcal{O}}\to{\mathrm{Ass}}$ or $\psi:{\mathcal{O}}\to\widetilde{{\mathrm{Ass}}}$ be a cocartesian fibration relative to the inert morphisms. A ${\mathcal{O}}$-operad is a cocartesian fibration $\phi:{\mathcal{C}}\to{\mathcal{O}}$ relative to the inert morphisms that is fibered with respect to $\Lambda_{\mathcal{O}}$. A generalized ${\mathcal{O}}$-operad is a cocartesian fibration $\phi:{\mathcal{C}}\to{\mathcal{O}}$ relative to the inert morphisms that is fibered with respect to $\Lambda^{\mathrm{gen}}_{\mathcal{O}}$. A (generalized) ${\mathcal{O}}$-monoidal $\infty$-category is a (generalized) ${\mathcal{O}}$-operad $\phi:{\mathcal{C}}\to{\mathcal{O}}$ that is a cocartesian fibration.
Definition 2.3. Let ${\mathcal{E}}\subset\mathrm{Fun}([1],{\mathrm{S}})$ be a full subcategory and $\Lambda$ a collection of functors of the form ${\mathrm{K}}^{\vartriangleleft}\to{\mathrm{S}}$ for some $\infty$-category ${\mathrm{K}}$ that send any morphism to a morphism of ${\mathcal{E}}$. We call a cocartesian fibration $\phi:{\mathcal{C}}\to{\mathrm{S}}$ relative to ${\mathcal{E}}$ fibered with respect to $\Lambda$ if for any functor $\alpha:{\mathrm{K}}^{\vartriangleleft}\to{\mathrm{S}}$ that belongs to $\Lambda$ the following two conditions hold: (1) the pullback ${\mathrm{K}}^{\vartriangleleft}\times_{{\mathrm{S}}}{\mathcal{C}}\to{\mathrm{K% }}^{\vartriangleleft}$ along $\alpha$, which is a cocartesian fibration, classifies a limit diagram ${\mathrm{K}}^{\vartriangleleft}\to\mathsf{Cat}_{\infty},$ (2) any $\phi$-cocartesian lift ${\mathrm{K}}^{\vartriangleleft}\to{\mathcal{C}}$ of $\alpha$ is a $\phi$-limit diagram.
Definition 2.35. Let ${\mathcal{M}}$ be an $\infty$-category weakly left tensored over some $\infty$-operad ${\mathcal{V}}.$ A morphism object of ${\mathrm{X}},{\mathrm{Y}}\in{\mathcal{M}}$ is an object $\mathrm{Mor}_{{\mathcal{M}}}({\mathrm{X}},{\mathrm{Y}})\in{\mathcal{V}}$ together with a multi-morphism $\alpha\in{\mathrm{Mul}}_{{\mathcal{M}}}(\mathrm{Mor}_{{\mathcal{M}}}({\mathrm{% X}},{\mathrm{Y}}),{\mathrm{X}};{\mathrm{Y}})$ that induces for every objects ${\mathrm{Z}}_{1},...,{\mathrm{Z}}_{\mathrm{n}}\in{\mathcal{V}}$ an equivalence ${\mathrm{Mul}}_{{\mathcal{V}}}({\mathrm{Z}}_{1},...,{\mathrm{Z}}_{\mathrm{n}};% \mathrm{Mor}_{{\mathcal{M}}}({\mathrm{X}},{\mathrm{Y}}))\simeq{\mathrm{Mul}}_{% {\mathcal{M}}}({\mathrm{Z}}_{1},...,{\mathrm{Z}}_{\mathrm{n}},{\mathrm{X}};{% \mathrm{Y}}).$ We call an $\infty$-category ${\mathcal{M}}$ weakly left tensored over ${\mathcal{V}}$ closed if for every ${\mathrm{X}},{\mathrm{Y}}\in{\mathcal{M}}$ there is a morphism object $\mathrm{Mor}_{{\mathcal{M}}}({\mathrm{X}},{\mathrm{Y}})\in{\mathcal{V}}$.
Definition 28. We introduce the following categories: (1) the full subcategory SpFrmS in $\mathbf{FrmS}$ generated by objects $(L,L_{s})$ where $L$ is a spatial frame, (2) the full subcategory SpLocS in $\mathbf{LocS}$ generated by objects $(L,L_{s})$ where $L$ is a spatial frame, (3) the full subcategory $\mathbf{ContFrmS}$ in $\mathbf{FrmS}$ generated by objects $(L,L_{s})$ where $L$ is a continuous frame, (4) the full subcategory $\mathbf{ContLocS}$ in $\mathbf{LocS}$ generated by objects $(L,L_{s})$ where $L$ is a continuous frame.
Definition 16 ([14, Definition 2.1]). A locally small space is a pair $(X,\mathcal{L}_{X})$, where $X$ is any set and $\mathcal{L}_{X}\subseteq\mathcal{P}(X)$ satisfies the following conditions: (LS1) $\emptyset\in\mathcal{L}_{X}$, (LS2) if $L,M\in\mathcal{L}_{X}$, then $L\cap M,L\cup M\in\mathcal{L}_{X}$, (LS3) $\forall x\in X\>\exists L_{x}\in\mathcal{L}_{X}\>\>x\in L_{x}$ (i. e., $\bigcup\mathcal{L}_{X}=X$). The family $\mathcal{L}_{X}$ will be called a smopology on $X$ and elements of $\mathcal{L}_{X}$ will be called small open subsets (or smops) in $X$.
Definition 21. Assume $(X,\mathcal{L}_{X})$ and $(Y,\mathcal{L}_{Y})$ are locally small spaces. Then a mapping $f:X\to Y$ is: $(a)$ bounded ([14, Definition 2.40]) if $\mathcal{L}_{X}$ is a refinement of $f^{-1}(\mathcal{L}_{Y})$, $(b)$ continuous ([14, Definition 2.40]) if $f^{-1}(\mathcal{L}_{Y})\cap_{1}\mathcal{L}_{X}\subseteq\mathcal{L}_{X}$, $(c)$ weakly continuous if $f^{-1}(\mathcal{L}_{Y}^{wo})\subseteq\mathcal{L}_{X}^{wo}$. The category of locally small spaces and their bounded continuous mappings is denoted by LSS ([14, Remark 2.46]). The full subcategory of $T_{0}$ locally small spaces is denoted by $\mathbf{LSS}_{0}$ ([15, Def. 33]).
Definition 8. A frame $L$ is spatial if $Spec(L)$ order generates (or: inf-generates) $L$, which means that each element of $L$ is a meet of primes.
Definition 20 ([15, Def. 31]). A locally small space $(X,\mathcal{L}_{X})$ is called $T_{0}$ (or Kolmogorov) if the family $\mathcal{L}_{X}$ separates points, which means $\forall x,y\in X\quad(x\neq y)\implies\exists V\in\mathcal{L}_{X}\mid V\cap\{x% ,y\}\mid=1.$
Definition 2. A frame homomorphism is a lattice homomorphism between frames preserving all joins. The category of frames and frame homomorphisms will be denoted by $\mathbf{Frm}$. The category of frames and right Galois adjoints of frame homomorphisms will be denoted by $\mathbf{Loc}$.
Definition 24. The category $\mathbf{FrmS}$ consists of pairs $(L,L_{s})$ with $L$ a frame and $L_{s}$ a sublattice with zero sup-generating $L$ (this means: every member of $L$ is the supremum of a subset of $L_{s}$) as objects and dominating compatible frame homomorphisms $h:(L,L_{s})\to(M,M_{s})$ as morphisms. Here a frame homomorphism $h:L\to M$ is called (1) dominating if $\quad\forall m\in M_{s}\quad\exists l\in L_{s}\quad h(l)\wedge m=m$ (then we shall also say that $h(L_{s})$ dominates $M_{s}$). (2) compatible if $\quad\forall m\in M_{s}\quad\forall l\in L_{s}\quad h(l)\wedge m\in M_{s}$ (then we shall also say that $h(L_{s})$ is compatible with $M_{s}$).
Definition 10 ([7, p. 286]). For $a,b\in L$, we say that $b$ is well-below $a$ (or: $b$ is way below $a$) and write $b\ll a$ if for each (up-)directed set $D\subseteq L$ such that $a\leq\sup D$ there exists $d\in D$ such that $b\leq d$.
Definition 3. For a frame $L$, its spectrum $Spec(L)$ is the set of non-unit primes of $L$: $Spec(L)=\{p\in L\setminus\{1\}:(p=a\wedge b)\implies(p=a\mbox{ or }p=b)\}.$ For $a\in L$, we define $\Delta_{L}(a)=\{p\in Spec(L):a\not\leq p\}.$ For a subset $S\subseteq L$, we set $\Delta_{L}(S)=\{\Delta_{L}(a):a\in S\}.$
Definition 11. A frame is called continuous if for each element $a\in L$ we have $a=\bigvee\{b\in L:b\ll a\}.$
Definition 26. The category $\mathbf{LocS}$ consists of pairs $(L,L_{s})$ with $L$ a frame and $L_{s}$ a sublattice with zero sup-generating $L$ as objects and special localic maps (i.e., right Galois adjoints $h_{*}:(M,M_{s})\to(L,L_{s})$ of dominating compatible frame homomorphisms $h:(L,L_{s})\to(M,M_{s})$) as morphisms.
Definition 1. A frame is a complete distributive lattice $L$ satisfying the (possibly infinite) distributive law $a\wedge\bigvee_{i\in I}b_{i}=\bigvee_{i\in I}(a\wedge b_{i})$ for $a,b_{i}\in L$ and $i\in I$.
Definition 22. We have the following full subcategories of $\mathbf{LSS}_{0}$: (1) the category $\mathbf{SobLSS}$ generated by the topologically sober objects $(X,\mathcal{L}_{X})$, i.e., such object that the topological space $(X,\mathcal{L}_{X}^{wo})$ is sober (compare [16, Def. 3.1]). (2) the category $\mathbf{LKSobLSS}$ generated by the topologically locally compact sober objects.
Definition 5. The set $\Delta_{L}(L)$ is a topology on $Spec(L)$, called the hull-kernel topology.
Definition 18 ([14, Def. 2.9]). For a locally small space $(X,\mathcal{L}_{X})$ we define the family $\mathcal{L}_{X}^{wo}=\mbox{the unions of subfamilies of }\mathcal{L}_{X}$ of weakly open sets. Then $\mathcal{L}_{X}^{wo}$ is the smallest topology containing $\mathcal{L}_{X}$.
Definition 2.3. Let $\lambda$ be a regular cardinal. A factorization system $(\mathcal{E},\mathcal{M})$ in a category $\mathcal{K}$ will be called $\lambda$-convenient if (1) $\mathcal{K}$ is $\mathcal{E}$-cowellpowered, i.e., if every object of $\mathcal{K}$ has only a set of $\mathcal{E}$-quotients, and (2) $\mathcal{M}$ is closed under $\lambda$-directed colimits, i.e., every $\lambda$-directed colimit of $\mathcal{M}$-morphisms has the property that (a) a colimit cocone consists of $\mathcal{M}$-morphisms, and (b) for every cocone of $\mathcal{M}$-morphisms, the factorizing morphism is in $\mathcal{M}$. $(\mathcal{E},\mathcal{M})$ is convenient if it is $\lambda$-convenient for some $\lambda$.
Definition 2.1. Let $\mathcal{K}$ be a category with a factorization system $(\mathcal{E},\mathcal{M})$ and $\lambda$ a regular cardinal. We say that an object $A$ is $\lambda$-generated w.r.t. $\mathcal{M}$ if its hom-functor $\mathcal{K}(A,-):\mathcal{K}\to\operatorname{\bf Set}$ preserves $\lambda$-directed colimits of $\mathcal{M}$-morphisms.
Definition 2.5. Let $\mathcal{K}$ be a cocomplete category with a $\lambda$-convenient factorization system $(\mathcal{E},\mathcal{M})$ where $\lambda$ a is regular cardinal. We say that $\mathcal{K}$ is $\mathcal{M}$-locally $\lambda$-generated if it has a set $\mathcal{A}$ of $\lambda$-generated objects w.r.t. $\mathcal{M}$ such that every object is a $\lambda$-directed colimit of objects from $\mathcal{A}$ and morphisms from $\mathcal{M}$. $\mathcal{K}$ is called $\mathcal{M}$-locally generated if it is $\mathcal{M}$-locally $\lambda$-generated for some regular cardinal $\lambda$.
